{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: failure is at a module handoff boundary (three collectors -> aggregation payload), not a single-function algorithm. REAL-INFRA/MOCK-HIDE: real network is not required; in-process fakes can still expose missing/overwritten source sections. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: no dependence on model judgment here, only pre-summary payload completeness. Rejection gate: System rejected because behavior text focuses on content assembly, not real HTTP/OS effects; Agentic rejected because it does not evaluate summary quality.","test_description":"Wire the real collection/orchestration modules with stubbed source clients returning distinct fixtures for metrics, issues, and deploy logs. Execute one report run and assert the exact object/string handed to summary-generation contains all three source sections and values (including source identifiers).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.16,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a `data unavailable` note for that section rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: this is cross-module error propagation (collector failure -> report assembly fallback), so Unit is too low. REAL-INFRA: outage can be simulated with an in-process failing client; no real network/OS primitive is required to reproduce fallback logic. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: behavior is deterministic fallback handling, not model-output quality. Rejection gate: System rejected because behavior text does not require real transport failure characteristics, only unavailable-source handling.","test_description":"Run orchestration with two source clients returning valid data and one source client raising timeout/503-style errors. Verify run completes, report includes normal sections for available sources, and unavailable source section contains `data unavailable` note instead of aborting.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.74,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The narrative summary accurately represents the key values present in the input data.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: correctness depends on what the real summary generator writes (faithfulness to key values), which a deterministic mock would hide. This is the deterministic-assertion trap: wrapper logic can be integration-tested, but factual representation quality requires real model behavior. MULTI-STEP: single model judgment step, so not Workflow. Rejection gate: Integration rejected because behavior text is explicitly about output accuracy, not routing/retries/payload formatting around the model call.","test_description":"Feed representative weekly datasets with known key values to the real summary-generation dependency and score factual faithfulness (key-value inclusion/correctness) over repeated runs with acceptance thresholds (e.g., no critical value corruption, bounded omission rate).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.74,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report — from data collection through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA/MOCK-HIDE: requires real external boundaries (HTTP/internal APIs + email transport + inbox receipt). In-process mocks can pass while real SMTP/API auth, TLS, routing, or inbox-delivery failures occur. LLM-DEP: although pipeline includes summary generation, this behavior’s pass condition is end-to-end delivery to inbox, not model quality. Rejection gate: Agentic rejected because behavior text does not assert generation correctness, only successful delivery of the complete report.","test_description":"Run the scheduled script in a production-like environment against reachable test endpoints and a real test mailbox. Assert one end-to-end run collects data, generates report artifact, sends email, and the configured recipient inbox receives the message with expected report attachment/body markers.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.08,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the email delivery service is unreachable, the generated report is saved to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: behavior spans real filesystem persistence plus cross-run retry semantics tied to scheduler/run lifecycle; real I/O and process boundaries are where failures surface (permissions, partial writes, stale state). MOCK-HIDE: mocked fs/scheduler can miss real persistence and next-run pickup defects. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: no dependence on model decision quality. Rejection gate: Integration rejected because behavior text explicitly requires local file save and retry on the next scheduled run, which crosses OS/runtime boundaries.","test_description":"Execute run N with email endpoint intentionally unreachable; verify report file is persisted on disk in configured fallback path. Execute run N+1 via the real scheduler trigger (or equivalent separate process invocation) with email restored; verify queued report is retried and successfully delivered, and retry state is cleared.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.81,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}}]}
